{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17510679","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17510679"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:33:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:33:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11653"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11653","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11653"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.04,0.3,0.03,0.44]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4274"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107091"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4274","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4274"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11653"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89555"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1400"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5749"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6970"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42638"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44530"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45074"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107091","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107091"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 22-year-old man presents with a painless swelling in his neck. He first noticed this about three weeks ago after he had an upper respiratory tract infection and sore throat. He is otherwise in good health. On examination there is a 3 cm smooth surfaced and firm lump to the immediate right of the tracheal cartilage. The lump moves with swallowing, but not on protrusion of the tongue. The rest of the neck examination is normal and there is no localised tenderness.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Thyroglossal cyst","Multinodular goitre","Cervical lymph node","Submandibular gland","Solitary thyroid adenoma"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ENeck swellings are common and can have a variety of causes. Understanding the anatomy and the symptomatology can help simplify the diagnostic process. The most frequently seen swellings arise from the thyroid or cervical lymph nodes. With its close relationship to the trachea, a thyroid related swelling can be observed to rise (~2cm) during swallowing and pause, before descending. This observation alone will help in the clarification of the site of origin of a neck swelling.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFrom its position and movement on swallowing, it is most likely that this patient has a \u003Cstrong\u003Esolitary thyroid adenoma. \u003C/strong\u003EAlthough usually asymptomatic, a toxic nodule can produce excess thyroid hormones, with the patient presenting with symptoms of thyroid over-activity. Sometimes - if the nodule is sufficiently large - it can compress surrounding structures and the patient present with dyspnoea or dysphonia. Usually, a toxic nodule will reach 3 cm before becoming overtly thyrotoxic so monitoring for such or malignant transformation depending on the cancer risk must be considered.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ethyroglossal cyst \u003C/strong\u003Eis a remnant of the thyroglossal duct, down which the embryonic thyroid gland descends from the foramen cecum of the tongue, tracing down midline. A thyroglossal cyst may form at any site of this duct, from the tongue base to the inferior part of the neck although the majority are found near the hyoid bone. Due to this relationship to the tongue, a thyroglossal cyst will move upwards when the tongue is protruded. Most of these cysts remain asymptomatic, but can present as a painful and tender swelling if infection sets in. The Sistrunk procedure is the definitive management for excision. Prior to this, it is prudent to check (ultrasonography) that a normal thyroid gland is present.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA\u003Cstrong\u003E multinodular goitre\u00a0is\u003C/strong\u003E generally asymptomatic and is typically found in areas of the world when there are dietary deficiencies in iodine. The swellings are often asymmetric. There is a similar rate of malignant transformation as with a solitary thyroid nodule. Compressive symptoms are well recognised. Management of a multinodular goitre will involve ultrasonography to determine its size, consistency and nodularity.\u003Csup\u003E \u003C/sup\u003EIf indicated, ultrasound can also be used to localise nodules for guided fine needle biopsy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEnlarged \u003Cstrong\u003Ecervical lymph nodes\u00a0\u003C/strong\u003Ewould be visible more laterally than described in this case. If the swelling and enlarged node secondary to the recent upper respiratory tract infection, it would be unusual to still be enlarged three weeks after the infection. In addition, it would still be tender and often have more than one lymph node enlarged. Any lymph node enlargement longer than that should be suspicious of a malignant process. In such cases the patient would often have constitutional symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe\u003Cstrong\u003E submandibular gland\u00a0\u003C/strong\u003Elies immediately under the jawbone and on the lateral side of the neck, making it an unlikely explanation for this patient\u0027s neck swelling. When the submandibular gland is enlarged the underlying problem is usually one of obstruction secondary to a duct calculus. Salivary gland malignancies are uncommon.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Only thyroid related structures move with swallowing."],"references":["Bomeli SR, LeBeau SO, Ferris RL. Evaluation of a thyroid nodule. Otolaryngol Clin North Am. 2010; 43:229-38","Mulita F, Anjum F. Thyroid adenoma - statpearls - NCBI bookshelf [Internet]. Thyroid Adenoma. 2022 [cited 2022Sep2]. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK562252/","Pearce EN. Toxic thyroid adenoma [Internet]. Toxic thyroid adenoma - Symptoms, diagnosis and treatment | BMJ Best Practice US. 2022 [cited 2022Sep2]. Available from: https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-us/34","Roland N, Bradley PJ. Neck Swellings. BMJ 2014;348:bmj.g1078"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89555"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11653"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89555","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89555"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-25T07:04:31+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-25T07:04:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4274"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107091"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGro